l photography offers a new account of how conflict photography developed in the decades before the First World War. It explores the ways the camera was used to impose order on subject populations in Africa and Asia and to generate propaganda for the public in Europe, where a visual economy of violence was rapidly taking shape.At the same time, the book reveals how photographs could escape the intentions of their creators, offering a means for colonial subjects to push back against oppression.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aWar photographyzFrancexHistory. 0aWar photographyzGreat BritainxHistory. 7aHISTORY / Modern / 19th Century.2bisacsh  aAbyssinia Expedition.  aAlice Seeley Harris.  aAnglo-Burmese War.  aBook Prize.  aBoxer rebellion.  aBritish Academy Book Prize.  aBritish Academy.  aBritish empire.  aCharles Tripp.  aConflict photography.  aCourting India.  aCrimean War.  aCundill History Prize.  aDimitris Xygalatas.  aDon McCullin.  aFatima Manji.  aFrench empire.  aGary Younge.  aKris Manjapra.  aLee Miller.  aLondon review Bookshop.  aMahdist War.  aPapyrus.  aPrize Winner.  aRabah az-Zubayr.  aRebecca Earle.  aRobert Baden-Powell.  aRosie Goldsmith.  aRusso-Japanese War.  aSecond Boer War.  aSpion Kop.  aSusan Sontag.  aTania Branigan.  aUndiscovered photographer.  aVoulet–Chanoine Mission.  aWilloughby Wallace Hooper.  aatrocity.  acolonial gaze.  acolonialism.  ahistory of violence.  aphotojournalism.  apropaganda.  asmall wars.  awar photography.1 aFoliard, Daniel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWagner, Kim A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2022 eBook-Packagez978311